'''William Howard "Bill" White''' (born June 16, 1954) is a [[United States]] [[politician]], member of the national and state [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] and current [[mayor]] of the [[city]] of [[Houston, Texas]] ([[January 2]], [[2004]]&ndash;present). He was elected mayor in 2003 and reelected in 2005 and 2007. Due to term limits he will have to step down as mayor in January 2010.<ref>[http://www.citymayors.com/mayors/houston_mayor.html CityMayors.com: Bill White]</ref>

Prior to serving as mayor, White served as [[U.S. Department of Energy|U.S. Deputy Secretary of Energy]] under [[President Clinton]] from 1993 to 1995 and he is an important political figure in Texas. He has been rated [[Governing Magazine]]'s Public Official of the Year for 2007.<ref>[http://www.myfoxhouston.com/myfox/pages/Home/Detail?contentId=4799768&version=1&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=TSTY&pageId=1.1.1 http://www.myfoxhouston.com/myfox/pages/Home/Detail?contentId=4799768&version=1&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=TSTY&pageId=1.1.1]</ref>

==Family and Personal Life==
White and his wife Andrea are the parents of three children, Will, Elena, and Stephen.

White was born and grew up in [[San Antonio]]. He is the son of two schoolteachers. He and his wife have helped lead numerous charitable and civic organizations. White is an avid biker and every year he leads Houston's annual "Bike to Work Day."<ref>[http://www.publicworks.houstontx.gov/bikeways/docs/summer_07_revised_3.pdf http://www.publicworks.houstontx.gov/bikeways/docs/summer_07_revised_3.pdf]</ref> He also created the annual biking event "Tour de Houston" through historic Houston neighborhoods.<ref>[http://www.edf.org/article.cfm?contentID=5483&campaign=299 Bicycle Commuting Enjoys a Rebirth]</ref> 

Bill White's wife [[Andrea White|Andrea]] is the daughter of Arthur John Ferguson (1917-2008), a [[Louisiana State University]] graduate in [[mechanical engineering]] originally from [[New Orleans]], and the former Patsi Wells, a native of [[Baton Rouge]].<ref>[http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/26088/Andrea_White/index.aspx?authorID=26088 http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/26088/Andrea_White/index.aspx?authorID=26088]</ref> Andrea White has written several [[novel]]s, one of which received the Texas Bluebonnet Award as well as the [[Golden Spur Award]].<ref>[http://www.literacyadvancehouston.org/champions_of_literacy/andrea_white.asp http://www.literacyadvancehouston.org/champions_of_literacy/andrea_white.asp]</ref>

White's son Stephen made the [[T-Mac]] All Star's fifteen year old AAU [[basketball]] team in Houston, which honors only the top 12 fifteen-year-old players in the city.{{Fact|date=January 2008}} White's daughter, Elena,  is currently enrolled at [[Rice University]].

The Whites are members of The St. Luke's United Methodist Church in Houston.<ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/096/000161610/ http://www.nndb.com/people/096/000161610/]</ref>

==Education and career==
Born in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]] as the son of public school teachers, White graduated from [[Winston Churchill High School (San Antonio, Texas)|Churchill High School]] before attending [[Harvard University]] on [[American Legion]] scholarships and graduating [[magna cum laude]] with a degree in economics. He then attended [[University of Texas School of Law|The University of Texas School of Law]], where he was elected editor-in-chief of its law review and graduated with highest honors.

White also served as an administrator on the Board of Directors for the Baylor College of Medicine.<ref>[http://www.nndb.com/edu/821/000112485/ http://www.nndb.com/edu/821/000112485/]</ref>

White began his career as a plaintiff [[lawyer]] at Susman Godfrey, LLP, a leading Houston law firm, from 1979 to 1993, where he practiced business litigation and anti-trust law, and eventually became partner. 

He served as [[U.S. Department of Energy|U.S. Deputy Secretary of Energy]] under [[Bill Clinton|President Clinton]] from 1993 to 1995. He organized Frontera Resources,<ref name=Azer1998>
{{cite journal
|url=http://azer.com/aiweb/categories/magazine/64_folder/64_articles/64_socar_frontera.html
|accessdate=2008-09-10
|title=Kursangi-Garabaghli Prospect
|journal= Azerbaijan International
|volume=6.4
|page=83
|date=Winter 1998
|year=1998
}}</ref> a developer of oil and gas in the [[Caspian Sea]] region, and was also the chairman of the [[Texas Democratic Party]], from 1995 to 1998. He was the president and [[chief executive officer|CEO]] of WEDGE Group, an energy, construction and real estate company, from 1997 to 2004.<ref name=HouBizJ_Jan2003>
